,Recommended,222140,9663155,"Posted: 29 March, 2014",all,Hrdkr,"Puddle is perfect in almost every sense. It's a not that typical indie game, it's challenging, have a fast pace, it's finally a real fun! This is a sole indie title I played till the credits since a long time.In this game, as you can see in the trailer, you control the liquid. The only method of control is to tilt a world a little. Basically the tilt creates a height difference between the liquid and the ground and the former accelerates due to gravity. You can use a keyboard arrow keys, but I personally recommend a gamepad triggers. So, you use just two keys to progress through the whole game.The game's world is divided to several chapters, which consists of number of levels. Each chapter represent a visually and aesthetically differing surround and the type of liquid you control in it. In some chapters you have different types of liquid in different levels. You starting at Watercourse with a coffee, proceeding as a water, then going to the Nursery transforming into weed killer (Sodium chlorate + copper oxide), become a fertilizer, travelling to the Laboratory, where the liquid turns into a hydrocarbon, oil, nytroglycerine, fruit juice + technecium solution... Human Body, Sewers, Rocket, Foundry, Nuclear Power Station at last! Each type of liquid has it's unique properties, water freezes and evaporates, nytroglycerine explodes when handled without a care and lava hardens when it's far from the heat source. The gravity in zero-gravity zone is actually zero, but in the centrifuge at the nuclear station with tremendous radiation levels the gravity alters after short distance travelled. You need to adapt you reflexes and to reinvent controls patterns with almost every new world's and liquid's conditions introduced in the game. And that's really fun.For me, the most funny part was a human body chapter. It starts like a real anatomically true human body but quickly you realize, that this 'body' has nothing to do with it's real world representation. The game's 'human body' is abstract as hell. As a chapter climax, your liquid get absorbed into the circulatory system, the view gets zoomed to 500x and you find youself in a blood cappilary system. You barely can control such a microscopic amounts of substances by tilting the world, so your gamepad's triggers, being rhythmically pushed one after another, pumps the blood and your precious solution of juice and technecium, which some fool drank, will jerkily flow through the capillaries. The fun is massive.Seems like game developers had a lot of ideas and that's great they realised a good part of it. THe game doesn't just exploiting the idea and brilliant representation of realistically looking liquid physics model through the whole game, which will be a tempting approach for some indie game studios. But no, they developing and evolving the original idea level after level, adapting and transforming it. And you just keep getting amazed when new properties and world conditions get introduced.At some levels the game is really challenging. Some levels can be passed only after 30 tries or so. Some levels' obvious difficulty can leave you infuriated and with no progress. And this is undoubtedly true for the very final level. There are no chances you can beat it in one sitting.This game is great. Small graphical inconsistencies here and there, like non-working antialiasing on 1440p cannot make it not great. The whole idea and implemention are great. If you're into indie gaming and your library is not like CoD 15 and BF 5 likes all the way up and down you should probably check it out. And I presume you'll not be dissatisfied."
